<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_ModuleInfo:
```c
int32 OS_ModuleInfo(osal_id_t module_id, OS_module_prop_t *module_prop)
{
    OS_common_record_t *         record;
    OS_module_internal_record_t *module;
    int32                        return_code;
    OS_object_token_t            token;

    /* Check parameters */
    OS_CHECK_POINTER(module_prop);

    memset(module_prop, 0, sizeof(OS_module_prop_t));

    return_code = OS_ObjectIdGetById(OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, module_id, &token);
    if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        record = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_global_module_table, token);
        module = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_module_table, token);

        strncpy(module_prop->name, record->name_entry, sizeof(module_prop->name) - 1);
        strncpy(module_prop->filename, module->file_name, sizeof(module_prop->filename) - 1);

        return_code = OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl(&token, module_prop);

        OS_ObjectIdRelease(&token);
    }

    return return_code;
}
```
</target_code>

int32 OS_ObjectIdGetById(OS_lock_mode_t lock_mode, osal_objtype_t idtype, osal_id_t id, OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    int32 return_code;

    return_code = OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit(lock_mode, idtype, token);
    if (return_code != OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        return return_code;
    }

    return_code = OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex(idtype, id, &token->obj_idx);
    if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        token->obj_id = id;

        /*
         * The "ConvertToken" routine will return with the global lock
         * in a state appropriate for returning to the caller, as indicated
         * by the "check_mode" parameter.
         *
         * Note If this operation fails, then it always unlocks the global for
         * all check_mode's other than NONE.
         */
        return_code = OS_ObjectIdConvertToken(token);
    }

    if (return_code != OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel(token);
    }

    return return_code;
}
...
void OS_ObjectIdRelease(OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish(token, NULL);
}

int32 OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token, OS_module_prop_t *module_prop)
{
    /*
     * Limiting strictly to POSIX-defined API means there is no defined
     * method to get information about a module contents.
     *
     * The "dlinfo()" function might return some interesting information
     * but this is actually a non-posix extension / platform-defined API.
     *
     * This returns success - although there is no information to add here,
     * the parent/shared layer information is still valid.
     */
    return OS_SUCCESS;
}

void OS_printf(const char *String, ...)
{
    va_list va;
    char    msg_buffer[OS_BUFFER_SIZE];
    int     actualsz;

    BUGCHECK_VOID(String != NULL)

    if (OS_SharedGlobalVars.GlobalState != OS_INIT_MAGIC_NUMBER)
    {
        /*
         * Catch some historical mis-use of the OS_printf() call.
         *
         * Typically OS_printf() should NOT be called before OS_API_Init().
         *
         * This was never guaranteed to work, particularly on a VxWorks
         * deployment where the utility task was enabled.
         *
         * However, some PSPs do this, particularly those that used POSIX
         * where it happened to work (because OS_printf just called printf).
         *
         * As a workaround, use the OS_DEBUG facility to dump the message,
         * along with a clue that this API is being used inappropriately.
         *
         * If debugging is not enabled, then this message will be silently
         * discarded.
         */
        OS_DEBUG("BUG: OS_printf() called when OSAL not initialized: %s", String);
    }
    else if (OS_SharedGlobalVars.PrintfEnabled)
    {
        /* Format and determine the size of string to write */
        va_start(va, String);
        actualsz = vsnprintf(msg_buffer, sizeof(msg_buffer), String, va);
        va_end(va);

        if (actualsz < 0)
        {
            /* unlikely: vsnprintf failed */
            actualsz = 0;
        }
        else if (actualsz >= OS_BUFFER_SIZE)
        {
            /* truncate */
            actualsz = OS_BUFFER_SIZE - 1;
        }

        msg_buffer[actualsz] = 0;

        OS_ConsoleWrite(OS_SharedGlobalVars.PrintfConsoleId, msg_buffer);
    }
}

explanation:
I examined the provided code and related definitions for constructs that would constitute statically unreachable code (code that can never be executed by any possible control flow). I found no such obvious instances. Specifically:

- OS_ModuleInfo: All statements are reachable depending on runtime values. The body guarded by if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) is conditionally reachable when OS_ObjectIdGetById returns success; the function returns the status otherwise. There are no statements after an unconditional return or any constant-false condition that would make code unreachable.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById / OS_ObjectIdRelease: The function has early returns for error cases and proceeds on success; all branches are reachable depending on return values. The transaction-cancel/finish calls are normal error handling control flow, not unreachable code.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET macro usage: Expands to an array indexing expression using the token; there is no evidence this produces dead code.

- OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl: Although it currently always returns OS_SUCCESS and contains only explanatory comments, it is a reachable function and its single return is the intended behavior; there is no unreachable statement within it.

- OS_printf: The flow is controlled by runtime globals (GlobalState, PrintfEnabled). Each branch (debug path vs normal formatting path) is reachable depending on those runtime values. There are no constant conditions that would render a branch permanently unreachable.

- Macros like OS_CHECK_POINTER / BUGCHECK / BUGCHECK_VOID are runtime checks; they may abort or handle errors at runtime but do not create statically unreachable code in the snippets provided.

Based on the supplied code and definitions, I could not identify any code fragment that is provably unreachable at compile time. If you have additional macro definitions (e.g., BUGCHECK/BUGCHECK_VOID) or build-time configuration that make some conditions constant (for example, if OS_SharedGlobalVars.GlobalState is a compile-time constant), please provide them — with that additional information some branches could become deterministically unreachable and should then be reported.
